Formally, we assume that the cost of production of one unit of good \(C\) is a random variable that depends on random noise \(\bm{X}\in\mathbb{R}^{m}\) and the decisions of a firm \(\bm{s}\in\mathbb{R}^{n}\). The firm knows that the noise is distributed according to a density function

\[\bm{X}\sim f(\cdot,\bm{\theta}),\bm{\theta}\in\mathbb{R}^{d}.\]However, it does not know the parameters of the distribution \(\bm{\theta}\).

The firm wants to minimize its marginal cost on average

\[c(\bm{s})=\mathbf{E}_{\bm{X}\sim f(\cdot,\bm{\theta})}(C(\bm{s},\bm{X})).\]

To achieve it, the firm decides to use the maximum likelihood estimates \(\widehat{\bm{\theta}}\) of \(\bm{\theta}\) using its data about the realizations of the noise. After that, the firm chooses an action that minimizes an estimated cost on average

\[\bm{s}_{\text{fin}}=\operatorname*{arg\,min}_{\bm{s}}\mathbf{E}_{\bm{X}\sim f (\cdot,\widehat{\bm{\theta}})}(C(\bm{s},\bm{X})).\]

The resulting cost \(c(\bm{s}_{\text{fin}})\) is a random variable because of randomness of the firm's sample \(S\). However, the asymptotic normality of MLE allows us to reason about a cost distribution.

We use the delta method to achieve this goal. By the asymptotic normality,

\[\sqrt{n}(\widehat{\bm{\theta}}-\bm{\theta})\xrightarrow{d}\mathrm{N}(0,\mathbf{ I}(\bm{\theta})^{-1}).\]

Further, by the delta method,

\[\sqrt{n}(\bm{s}_{\text{fin}}-\bm{s}^{*})\xrightarrow{d}\sqrt{n}\left(\frac{ \partial\bm{s}}{\partial\bm{\theta}}\right)^{\mathsf{T}}(\widehat{\bm{\theta} }-\bm{\theta}).\]

Finally, by the second-order delta method,

\[n(c(\bm{s}_{\text{fin}})-c(\bm{s}^{*})) \xrightarrow{d}n\nabla c(\bm{s}^{*})^{\mathsf{T}}(\bm{s}_{ \text{fin}}-\bm{s}^{*})+n(\bm{s}_{\text{fin}}-\bm{s}^{*})^{\mathsf{T}}\frac{ \nabla^{2}c(\bm{s}^{*})}{2}(\bm{s}_{\text{fin}}-\bm{s}^{*})\] \[=n(\bm{s}_{\text{fin}}-\bm{s}^{*})^{\mathsf{T}}\frac{\nabla^{2}c( \bm{s}^{*})}{2}(\bm{s}_{\text{fin}}-\bm{s}^{*}).\]

Thus, the marginal cost will be distributed approximately as generalized chi-squared distribution. The expected marginal cost will be approximately

\[c^{e}=\mathbf{E}_{S}(c(\bm{s}_{\text{fin}}))\approx c(\bm{s}^{*})+\frac{1}{2n} \operatorname{Tr}\!\left(\nabla^{2}c(\bm{s}^{*})\left(\frac{\partial\bm{s}}{ \partial\bm{\theta}}\right)^{\mathsf{T}}\mathbf{I}(\bm{\theta})^{-1}\frac{ \partial\bm{s}}{\partial\bm{\theta}}\right)\!.\]

Therefore, one of the natural choices for the dependency of expected marginal cost on the number of data points is

\[c^{e}(n)=a+\frac{b}{n}.\]

